<subSubSection id="6ADEE2B193F4716AC42E40A361628978" pageId="9" pageNumber="36" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="0C8BA7C8991CDBE91214697C23D77CE2" pageId="9" pageNumber="36">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D9301B942C9D835704F9BA30888DF9E2" pageId="9" pageNumber="36">
The 31 species of this genus (
<bibRefCitation id="731DF7A72DBF803AA15F42E72A39114D" pageId="9" pageNumber="36">ThripsWiki 2013</bibRefCitation>
) are typical flower-living thrips, and most are associated with plants of the family 
<taxonomicName id="3268FDF2FF1D27294E913735DF79A338" genus="Fabaceae" lsidName="Fabaceae" pageId="9" pageNumber="36" rank="genus">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
. They can cause slight damage to the flowers, but only 
<taxonomicName id="ACC4F9F7156A7684C6B5F318BB730308" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Odontothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Odontothrips confusus" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confusus">Odontothrips confusus</taxonomicName>
is an important pest (
<bibRefCitation id="1B04B8D20B349433670A7D4BBDF11A2C" author="Pitkin, BR" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) (Entomology)" pageId="15" pageNumber="42" pagination="371 - 402" title="A revision of the flower-living genus Odontothrips Amyot and Serville (Thysanoptera: Thripidae)." volume="26" year="1972">Pitkin 1972</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="715D55155E8D8885556083F2F7E7D65B" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Megalurothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megalurothrips peculiaris" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peculiaris">Megalurothrips peculiaris</taxonomicName>
which sensorium base is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="3F53737C3DB9A31C2FC5108C2977F06E" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Odontothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Odontothrips" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Odontothrips</taxonomicName>
, and recorded from India and Bangladesh. This genus is included in the 
<taxonomicName id="AC5E4D6E07C136F03B5D704A1E6358CC" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Megalurothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megalurothrips" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Megalurothrips</taxonomicName>
genus-group (
<bibRefCitation id="2642A65666049A61477C0DAC4DF3D668" author="Mound, LA" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Scandinavica" pageId="14" pageNumber="41" pagination="153 - 17" title="Phylogenetic relationships between some genera of Thripidae (Thysanoptera)." volume="15" year="1981 a">Mound and Palmer 1981a</bibRefCitation>
) and four species have been recorded from Iran (
<bibRefCitation id="961D08D523B79866B9E6387B8351A556" author="Mirab-balou, M" journalOrPublisher="Munis Entomology and Zoology" pageId="13" pageNumber="40" pagination="944 - 952" title="The Megalurothrips genus-group in Iran (Thysanoptera: Thripidae)." volume="6" year="2011 b">Mirab-balou and Chen 2011b</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="3126E8BD2858BFC8794C1915935821F3" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Odontothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Odontothrips confusus" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confusus">Odontothrips confusus</taxonomicName>
Priesner is widely distributed in Iran, and populations are sometimes high on alfalfa, 
<taxonomicName id="3A1F86E63A1C3D73AAFA4C0564D9CDA2" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Medicago" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Medicago sativa" order="Fabales" pageId="9" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sativa">Medicago sativa</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
